new tales alike are mobilized in the effort. People's choices of belonging are flexible and often blatantly pragmatic. Some will never renounce their original 'nation,' while others gladly assume two or three national identities in a lifetime, all of them with a deeply felt commitment. In The Shifting Foundations of Modern Nation-States, Sima Godfrey and Frank Unger have gathered together a distinguished, multidisciplinary group of authors to discuss national myths from Europe, North America, and Asia. Just as the plurality of nations implies diverse voices and distinct narratives, the authors, coming from different disciplines and backgrounds, represent multiple discourses on the theme of nationhood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aNation-statexHistory. 0aNation-state. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Nationalism & Patriotism.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Benedict, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Ramsay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerenczi, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGodfrey, Sima, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHeinemann-Gruder, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKontler, László, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPetrusewicz, Marta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchirmer, Dietmar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUnger, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUnger, Frank, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://do